Jamaica Ave., north side, east from 169th Street, showing in a set of two views in the foreground the home of G. Sayres in 1873; beyond it is that of Geo. Dawson.  A private Sanitarium occupied the house in the foreground in 1913.  It was demolished in August 1925.  On the site now are a group of taxpayers.

May 1923.
View 2: April 1925.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Jamaica Ave., south side, between 169th and 170th Streets, showing in a set of two views the U. Pearsall house of 1873.  J. Hoagland was the owner in 1891.

May 1923.
View 2: February 8, 1924.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Jamaica Ave., south side, between 169th and 170th Streets, showing in a set of two views the U. Pearsall house of 1873.  J. Hoagland was the owner in 1891.

May 1923.
View 2: February 8, 1924.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(1) and (2)
168-38 to 168-48 Jamaica Ave., south side, opposite 169th Street.  From right to left are the following homes: B.B. Wood 1873, Edward 1891, (small two story frame, next to three story brick); Mrs. King 1873, T.J. Wayne 1891, (building with one story front); S.J. Young 1873, G. Durland 1891 (next to last mentioned house); and that of Mrs. Mills 1873, G. Darby 1891 (seen in the background of view No. 2).

February 8, 1924.
View 2: February 2, 1924.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(3)
The same, years later.  The small two-story frame house was razed and a one-story taxpayer erected on the site.  It is occupied by the fish market.

April 6, 1932
P.L. Sperr
